70 (C) One mental health advocate, appointed by the President of the Senate; and
71 (D) One mental health advocate, appointed by the Speaker of the House of
72 Representatives.
73 (c) Health care providers shall be required to report suspected violations by health insurers
74 of the mental health parity requirements contained in Code Sections 33-1-27 and
75 33-21A-13.
76 (d) The panel shall establish a simple and intuitive process to receive complaints reported
77 by health care providers pursuant to subsection (c) of this Code section. The panel shall
78 evaluate submitted complaints to determine whether a health insurer is in violation of
79 mental health parity laws. Based on such evaluation, the panel shall make
80 recommendations as to appropriate punitive actions, if any, that may be warranted for a
81 health insurer to the Commissioner of Insurance for violations of Code Section 33-1-27 and
82 to the commissioner of community health for violations of Code Section 33-21A-13.
83 (e) The panel shall be authorized to:
84 (1) Receive and analyze required reports from insurance companies and health care
85 providers;
86 (2) Request additional information from health insurers regarding potential mental health
87 parity violations, including determinations of medical necessity;
88 (3) Create and review educational materials for consumers and health care providers
89 relating to compliance with mental health parity laws. Such educational materials shall
90 include information on the concept of mental health parity, individuals' rights, and the
91 complaint processes established pursuant to subsection (e) of Code Section 33-1-27,
92 subsection (e) of Code Section 33-21A-13, and subsection (d) of this Code section. All
93 such educational materials shall be culturally and linguistically sensitive, to the extent
94 practicable; available in multiple languages; widely distributed; and offered in various
95 formats, such as on a public website, in a brochure, and in written documentation; and
